SIMPLE: institute
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Institute
<hw>In"sti*tute</hw> <pr>(⟦icr⟧n"st⟦icr⟧*t⟦umac⟧t)</pr>, <pos>p.
a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>institutus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>instituere</ets>
to place in, to institute, to instruct; pref. <ets>in-</ets> in +
<ets>statuere</ets> to cause to stand, to set. See
<er>Statute</er>.]</ety> <def>Established; organized; founded.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They have but few laws. For to a people so instruct and
<qex>institute</qex>, very few to suffice.</q> <rj><qau>Robynson (More's
Utopia).</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 772 --></p>

<p><ent>Institute</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Institute
<hw>In"sti*tute</hw> <pr>(⟦icr⟧n"st⟦icr⟧*t⟦umac⟧t)</pr>, <pos>v.
t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Instituted</conjf>
<pr>(⟦icr⟧n"st⟦icr⟧*t⟦umac⟧`t⟦ecr⟧d)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Instituting</conjf>.]</vmorph>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To set up; to establish; to ordain; <as>as, to
<ex>institute</ex> laws, rules, etc.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To originate and establish; to found; to organize;
<as>as, to <ex>institute</ex> a court, or a society</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Whenever any from of government becomes destructive of these ends
it is the right of the people to alter or to abolish it, and to
<qex>institute</qex> a new government.</q> <rj><qau>Jefferson (Decl. of
Indep. ).</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To nominate; to appoint.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>We <qex>institute</qex> your Grace⟦br⟧
To be our regent in these parts of France.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To begin; to commence; to set on foot; <as>as, to
<ex>institute</ex> an inquiry; to <ex>institute</ex> a
suit.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And haply <qex>institute</qex>⟦br⟧
A course of learning and ingenious studies.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To ground or establish in principles and rudiments;
to educate; to instruct.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If children were early <qex>instituted</qex>, knowledge would
insensibly insinuate itself.</q> <rj><qau>Dr. H. More.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Eccl. Law)</fld> <def>To invest with the spiritual
charge of a benefice, or the care of souls.</def>
<rj><au>Blackstone.</au></rj></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To originate; begin; commence; establish; found;
erect; organize; appoint; ordain.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Institute</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Institute
<hw>In"sti*tute</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>institutum</ets>: cf.
F. <ets>institut</ets>. See <er>Institute</er>, <pos>v. t.</pos> &
<pos>a.</pos>]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of instituting; institution.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧Water sanctified by Christ's
<xex>institute</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>That which is instituted, established, or fixed, as
a law, habit, or custom.</def> <rj><au>Glover.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Hence: An elementary and necessary principle; a
precept, maxim, or rule, recognized as established and authoritative;
usually in the plural, a collection of such principles and precepts;
esp., a comprehensive summary of legal principles and decisions; <as>as,
the <ex>Institutes</ex> of Justinian; Coke's <ex>Institutes</ex> of the
Laws of England</as>. Cf. <er>Digest</er>, <pos>n.</pos></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They made a sort of <qex>institute</qex> and digest of
anarchy.</q> <rj><qau>Burke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To make the Stoics' <qex>institutes</qex> thy own.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>An institution; a society established for the
promotion of learning, art, science, etc.; a college; <as>as, the
<ex>Institute</ex> of Technology</as>; The Massachusetts
<ex>Institute</ex> of Technology; also, a building owned or occupied by
such an institute; <as>as, the Cooper <ex>Institute</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Scots Law)</fld> <def>The person to whom an estate
is first given by destination or limitation.</def>
<rj><au>Tomlins.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Institutes of medicine</b></col>, <cd>theoretical
medicine; that department of medical science which attempts to account
philosophically for the various phenomena of health as well as of
disease; physiology applied to the practice of medicine.</cd>
<rj><au>Dunglison.</au></rj> </cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Instituter</ent>⟦br⟧
